{"id":"royal-tree:islamic-atlas:91","names":{"en":"Seljuq","tr":"Selçuklular","ar":"al-Salājika"},"country":["EG","IQ","IR","SY","TM","UZ"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1038,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"91","atlas_name_en_original":"The Seljuqs","parent_tribe":"Kınık boyu (Oğuz Türkleri)","ethnic_origin":"Türk (Oğuz)","capital":"İsfahan (Büyük); Merv (erken); Şam (Suriye); Berdisîr (Kirmân)","region_primary":"İran, Irak, Suriye, Kirmân","regions_all":"Horasan; İsfahan; Bağdat; Suriye; Kirmân; Mâverâünnehir (geçici)","geographic_zone":"Mısır/Şam","predecessor":"Büveyhîler (Irak); Gazneliler (Horasan)","successor":"Hârezmşahlar; İldenizliler; Zengîler; çeşitli atabeglikler","government_type":"Atabeglik","religious_orientation":"Sünnî","narrative_en":"The Seljuqs represent one of the most decisive turning points in Islamic history and the founding force of the Turco-Islamic synthesis. Descending from the Qınıq clan of the Oghuz Turks, the Seljuqs defeated the Ghaznavids at the Battle of Dandanaqan (1040), dominated Khurasan, and within fifteen years took Būyid Baghdad, initiating the resurgence of Sunni Islam. Tughril Beg received the title 'Sultan of the East and West' from the Abbasid caliph, permanently institutionalizing the sultanate in Islamic politics. Alp Arslan's victory at Manzikert (1071) opened Anatolia to the Turco-Islamic world, while the era of Malik Shāh and his vizier Niẓām al-Mulk constituted one of the most brilliant administrative periods in Islamic history. The Niẓāmiyya madrasas institutionalized the Islamic educational system, building the intellectual infrastructure of Sunni orthodoxy. Branches established in Iraq, Kirman, Syria, and Anatolia under the Great Seljuq umbrella redrew the political map of the Islamic world.","importance_level":"Kritik","capital_lat":"33.51","capital_lon":"36.29","century_start":11,"century_end":12}}
